Commuters may face longer travel times as roads and railways are set to be impacted by a snow warning put in place. Scotland is expected to freeze in sub-zero temperatures as the Met Office warned that up to 5cm of snow could blanket northern areas this evening. By Tuesday evening, Inverness and nearby areas could be covered in 19cm of the white stuff, according to weather maps supplied by WXCharts.   The warning is in place from 6pm until midnight today, with a snow and ice warning covering all of the begining of the week as well. The weather warnings come after a weather phenomenon, sudden stratospheric warming (SSW), took place last month and was closely monitored by forecasters as it played a large part in 2018’s Beast from the East. FOLLOW BELOW FOR THE LATEST UPDATES…  